WEBVTT

00:00.934 --> 00:02.533
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH ON TV]

00:02.600 --> 00:03.800
[MAN LAUGHS ON TV]

00:04.633 --> 00:06.200
Eating junk food with your friends,

00:06.266 --> 00:08.800
watching TV while your brain
turns to tapioca,

00:08.867 --> 00:10.700
this is what America's all about.

00:11.000 --> 00:12.133
JO: Hey, guys, [SIGHS]

00:12.200 --> 00:14.300
I'm gonna head on over
to the convalescent hospital

00:14.400 --> 00:15.734
and read to some of the patients.

00:15.800 --> 00:16.900
You guys want to come help?

00:16.967 --> 00:18.000
Sure.

00:18.066 --> 00:19.567
-Right.
-Yeah.

00:20.500 --> 00:22.900
'Cause then I thought that we could
go over to the fertilizer store

00:22.967 --> 00:24.633
and roll around in the fertilizer

00:24.700 --> 00:26.367
until the grass
grows out of our heads.

00:26.600 --> 00:27.600
Yeah.

00:27.667 --> 00:29.200
-Right.
-Sure.

00:29.600 --> 00:33.300
Okay, what is so fascinating
that you've all become zombies?

00:33.700 --> 00:34.900
Spanish game show.

00:34.967 --> 00:36.200
JO: I'm sorry, I have to ask.

00:36.266 --> 00:37.734
Since none of you speak Spanish,

00:37.800 --> 00:40.767
why are you watching
a game show in Spanish?

00:40.834 --> 00:42.834
My cousin Carlos
is supposed to be on it.

00:42.900 --> 00:44.800
-Oh, really? The one from Mexico?
-Hmm.

00:44.867 --> 00:46.734
The one who taught Lizzie's dad
how to dance?

00:46.800 --> 00:48.100
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

00:48.900 --> 00:50.400
Carlos is such a cool guy.

00:50.500 --> 00:52.133
I mean, he's always thinking
of ways to make money.

00:52.200 --> 00:54.867
Yeah, he taught me how to ride a bike,
how to climb a tree,

00:54.934 --> 00:56.200
and how to swim.

00:56.767 --> 00:57.967
He gave me the family discount,

00:58.033 --> 00:59.934
but I'm still paying off
the swim lessons.

01:00.367 --> 01:02.900
Carlos and some of his friends
are going to be on the show next week.

01:02.967 --> 01:04.734
Oh. That's terrific,
but I still don't think

01:04.800 --> 01:07.500
you guys should waste your whole
afternoon watching television.

01:07.567 --> 01:09.667
I mean, if your homework is done,

01:09.734 --> 01:12.333
then you could be out
riding your bikes or...

01:13.033 --> 01:14.400
[LAUGHING]

01:16.567 --> 01:18.333
...playing soccer or...

01:18.400 --> 01:20.000
[CONTINUES LAUGHING]

01:24.300 --> 01:26.200
Why is Montezuma chasing that girl?

01:26.867 --> 01:28.133
We don't know.

01:28.533 --> 01:30.633
Is that host's suntan real?

01:30.700 --> 01:32.200
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:33.500 --> 01:34.500
Who knows?

01:35.033 --> 01:36.100
Potato chip?

01:40.266 --> 01:42.834
[LAUGHS, SPEAKS SPANISH]

01:42.934 --> 01:44.800
[LAUGHS]

01:44.867 --> 01:46.867
[THEME SONG PLAYING]

01:49.333 --> 01:51.400
<i>If you believe</i>

01:52.867 --> 01:55.867
<i>We've got a picture-perfect plan</i>

01:56.400 --> 01:58.600
<i>We've got you fooled</i>

01:59.767 --> 02:03.266
<i>'Cause we only do the best we can</i>

02:04.934 --> 02:07.333
<i>And sometimes we make it</i>

02:08.700 --> 02:11.133
<i>And sometimes we fake it</i>

02:12.100 --> 02:17.367
<i>But we'll get one step closer</i>
<i>each and every day</i>

02:18.100 --> 02:21.166
<i>We will figure it out on the way</i>

02:25.500 --> 02:27.500
[SCHOOL BELL RINGING]

02:31.567 --> 02:32.667
Oh.

02:32.734 --> 02:36.433
That must be that new kid from, um...
That-that place.

02:36.500 --> 02:38.000
Indonesia. His name's Li.

02:42.433 --> 02:43.600
Hi, Li.

02:44.300 --> 02:45.900
I'm Lizzie and this is Gordo.

02:46.600 --> 02:48.433
You're really lucky
to have Mr. Dig this week.

02:48.500 --> 02:50.133
He's a really cool substitute.

02:50.200 --> 02:52.400
Oh, and if you need anyone
to show you around,

02:52.467 --> 02:53.467
just let me know, okay?

02:54.600 --> 02:55.900
I am Li.

02:56.700 --> 03:00.767
Yes, and, um,
I'm Lizzie and this is Gordo.

03:00.834 --> 03:04.266
Do you need anyone to show you around?
You know, give you the 4-1-1?

03:04.767 --> 03:06.100
4-1-1?

03:07.533 --> 03:10.166
[IN WESTERN ACCENT] What we have here
is a failure to communicate.

03:10.767 --> 03:13.800
Uh, so, Li, are your other classes
cool so far?

03:14.166 --> 03:16.500
Oh, yes, I have other classes.

03:16.834 --> 03:18.066
Uh-huh. And, um...

03:18.133 --> 03:19.767
[CLEARS THROAT] How are they?

03:20.066 --> 03:21.433
Fine. How are you?

03:22.433 --> 03:24.166
[SCREAMS]

03:24.667 --> 03:25.767
I'm fine, thanks.

03:27.867 --> 03:31.600
He's cute, but he understands
even less than Ethan Craft.

03:31.800 --> 03:34.433
Hello, good morning, and welcome
to another exciting edition

03:34.500 --> 03:37.033
of Mr. Dig's
"People, Places and Things."

03:37.100 --> 03:38.900
I'm Mr. Digs, you're people,

03:38.967 --> 03:42.600
we're in a place,
and this is the thing. [CHUCKLES]

03:43.100 --> 03:44.100
Who can tell me what it is?

03:44.166 --> 03:46.500
Uh, it's a magical
three-sided elf badge

03:46.567 --> 03:49.033
which renders the wearer invisible
so he can enter the realm

03:49.100 --> 03:51.000
of the Forest King
in <i>Lord of The Rings.</i>

03:52.400 --> 03:54.633
No. It's a lip stretcher.

03:55.100 --> 03:58.333
The SuyÃ¡ Indian men
of the Xingu River in the Amazon Basin

03:58.400 --> 04:01.900
use this to pull their lower lips
out to here. [CHUCKLES]

04:02.700 --> 04:04.400
That's exactly what
I was going to guess.

04:04.767 --> 04:07.066
-That hurts.
-Indeed it does, Mr. Gordon.

04:07.433 --> 04:09.033
But in the Amazon Basin,

04:09.100 --> 04:10.934
it's the look the chicks dig big-time.

04:11.033 --> 04:12.033
[ALL LAUGH]

04:12.100 --> 04:14.767
Hey, different cultures
have different standards of beauty.

04:14.834 --> 04:17.100
Chinese prize tiny feet.

04:17.166 --> 04:20.000
Middle Eastern cultures
are fascinated with the eyes,

04:20.066 --> 04:23.433
and some African tribes
like elongated necks

04:23.500 --> 04:24.900
and enlarged ear lobes.

04:24.967 --> 04:26.567
Ooh, that's weird.

04:26.633 --> 04:28.433
Well, it may be weird
to you, Mr. Tudgeman,

04:28.500 --> 04:29.834
but the women in eastern Africa

04:29.900 --> 04:32.700
would find you disturbingly pale
and bizarrely dressed.

04:33.033 --> 04:34.567
That's how the women here find him.

04:35.900 --> 04:38.433
The point is,
is that our culture is a lot richer

04:38.500 --> 04:41.166
because of the contributions
of other cultures.

04:42.100 --> 04:45.033
It just so happens, today, we have
a new student in our class, uh,

04:45.100 --> 04:46.300
from Indonesia.

04:46.867 --> 04:48.133
Li Tarak.

04:50.000 --> 04:52.700
Maybe you could tell us how
we could benefit from your culture.

04:53.133 --> 04:54.934
Uh, again, sorry?

04:55.000 --> 04:57.033
Could you tell us
about something from Indonesia?

04:57.800 --> 05:00.000
Yes, I am from Indonesia.

05:00.066 --> 05:01.500
[ALL GIGGLE]

05:03.033 --> 05:04.467
This might take a while.

05:04.967 --> 05:06.100
So it takes a while.

05:06.166 --> 05:07.834
We're here to learn
about other cultures.

05:08.300 --> 05:09.367
And just to make sure we do,

05:09.433 --> 05:11.600
I want you to write a report
on a different culture.

05:11.667 --> 05:14.000
It could be your native culture
or you can pick a foreign one,

05:14.066 --> 05:16.834
and tell us what we can learn
from people and their customs.

05:18.166 --> 05:20.333
Doesn't sound as good
as a free trip to the water park.

05:20.400 --> 05:21.367
[YELLS]

05:24.133 --> 05:27.400
[SIGHS] Mom, Dad,
where did I come from?

05:28.867 --> 05:30.967
I thought we had that talk
a while back.

05:31.033 --> 05:32.867
Was there something
you didn't understand, honey?

05:32.934 --> 05:34.066
Something you wanna talk about?

05:34.133 --> 05:36.700
Ew! Ew, no! Not like that!

05:36.767 --> 05:39.567
I mean, like,
where did our family come from?

05:39.633 --> 05:42.233
Oh. Well, honey, you know
I'm from Walla Walla, Washington.

05:42.300 --> 05:43.667
And I'm from Kalamazoo.

05:44.367 --> 05:46.467
I knew it.
My parents are from outer space.

05:47.233 --> 05:49.333
I mean, like,
what country did we come from?

05:49.400 --> 05:51.800
I have to write a book report
on a foreign culture.

05:51.867 --> 05:53.433
Well, Sam, what?

05:53.500 --> 05:55.700
-Your family is Scottish or Irish?
-[BAGPIPES PLAYING]

05:55.767 --> 05:57.066
SAM: Well, something like that.

05:57.133 --> 05:59.100
What about you, sweetheart?
Aren't you Swiss?

05:59.166 --> 06:02.066
Swiss, German, Hungarian, Polish.

06:02.133 --> 06:03.667
All the countries with heavy food.

06:03.734 --> 06:05.633
Guess I'll still have
to find a culture. [SIGHS]

06:05.700 --> 06:08.100
Well, whatever I am,
I'm proud to be it.

06:17.633 --> 06:18.633
Thanks, Lanny.

06:19.100 --> 06:20.100
Hey, Matt...

06:20.166 --> 06:22.767
I can't talk now, Dad.
I'm looking for Lanny.

06:22.834 --> 06:24.767
He's in with the dried beans, son.

06:27.433 --> 06:28.900
You can't hide in the pantry.

06:29.333 --> 06:32.967
You've transgressed the rules.
You've opened a can of worms.

06:33.367 --> 06:35.767
Now, I'm hiding wherever I want,

06:35.834 --> 06:37.400
and you'll never find me.

06:37.467 --> 06:40.266
This is Hide-and-Go-Seek
like you've never seen it before.

06:40.333 --> 06:42.800
You have been warned.

06:48.600 --> 06:49.600
Thanks, Lanny.

06:50.066 --> 06:52.300
Hey, you guys remember
my cousin Carlos

06:52.367 --> 06:53.633
from my birthday party, right?

06:53.700 --> 06:55.467
Lizzie! [CHUCKLES]

06:56.133 --> 06:58.600
Mwah! [LAUGHS]

06:58.667 --> 07:00.767
No, no, I'm more of a shake-hands guy.

07:00.834 --> 07:02.367
Why does he always kiss people?

07:02.433 --> 07:04.567
That's what some people do
in Mexico City.

07:06.767 --> 07:09.133
How come Ethan Craft
can't be from Mexico City?

07:09.700 --> 07:12.800
You guys remember that game show
my cousin's supposed to be on?

07:12.867 --> 07:14.900
-Well, his teammates canceled on him.
-[CARLOS SCOFFS]

07:14.967 --> 07:17.066
Their dad's making them
go to their sister's wedding.

07:17.133 --> 07:18.266
CARLOS: So cruel.

07:18.333 --> 07:20.767
If the happy couple
is so much "in love,"

07:20.834 --> 07:22.000
they can't wait a week?

07:22.767 --> 07:24.133
So you can't find anybody else?

07:24.200 --> 07:25.433
I tried to recruit replacements

07:25.500 --> 07:27.700
from the retirement home
my parents manage.

07:27.767 --> 07:29.667
I take it they weren't too good
at the stunts.

07:29.734 --> 07:33.000
On the contrary, my friend,
they were very good.

07:33.066 --> 07:35.066
-[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]
-[JUBILANT MUSIC PLAYS]

07:35.700 --> 07:37.567
[TIRES SQUEALING]

07:38.066 --> 07:39.834
But there's this puppet show
that afternoon

07:39.900 --> 07:41.300
and they're not willing to miss it,

07:41.367 --> 07:44.233
so there goes my chance
at the <i>dinero y fabulosos regalos.</i>

07:44.900 --> 07:46.734
Money and fabulous prizes.

07:48.166 --> 07:50.567
Money? Prizes? I'm up. I'm awake.

07:50.633 --> 07:53.066
Well, I mean,
we could be your teammates.

07:53.367 --> 07:55.133
Uh, two problems.

07:55.200 --> 07:56.834
One, we don't know the rules
of the game show,

07:56.900 --> 07:58.900
and two,
we don't speak a word of Spanish.

07:58.967 --> 08:01.700
I can speak some Spanish.
I know how to say,

08:01.767 --> 08:03.500
"Thanks for
the Christmas present, Grandpa."

08:03.567 --> 08:05.433
And, "I am off the phone."

08:05.500 --> 08:08.200
Yeah, and Carlos
totally speaks Spanish.

08:08.266 --> 08:10.033
I mean, he can translate for us,

08:10.100 --> 08:12.900
tell us what stunts to do
and we can do 'em.

08:13.633 --> 08:16.233
This way I can do research for
my report about a foreign culture,

08:16.300 --> 08:18.667
and win fabulous prizes and dinero.

08:18.867 --> 08:21.567
Now, that's a homework assignment
that relates to my life.

08:21.633 --> 08:22.700
Then we'll do it!

08:22.767 --> 08:25.266
The four of us will go
for <i>El Oro de Montezuma!</i>

08:25.767 --> 08:26.834
[BLOWS WHISTLE]

08:27.100 --> 08:29.567
LIZZIE: Go, go, go, go!
Go, go, go, come on!

08:30.100 --> 08:31.300
Come on, come on, come on...

08:33.266 --> 08:35.266
-Come on, come on.
-Run, run!

08:35.333 --> 08:36.333
[SQUEALING] Yes!

08:36.400 --> 08:38.633
Fourteen seconds! Excellent.

08:38.700 --> 08:40.066
Okay, so, we've made it onto the show,

08:40.133 --> 08:42.900
we've got our parents' permission,
we've got a handle on the stunts.

08:42.967 --> 08:44.567
So, Miranda and I
think it would be good

08:44.633 --> 08:47.133
if we learned some Spanish phrases
we'll need for the show.

08:47.200 --> 08:48.600
Uh, Miranda?

08:49.233 --> 08:51.700
"Hi, Alex. This is my favorite show."

08:51.900 --> 08:54.967
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

08:55.033 --> 08:57.333
"Great pants, Alex.
Where did you get them?"

08:57.400 --> 08:59.967
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

09:01.967 --> 09:05.333
"Let's go, go, go for the gold! Yay!"

09:05.400 --> 09:08.500
[SPEAKING SPANISH, CHEERING LOUDLY]

09:09.400 --> 09:10.500
[CHEERING SOFTLY]

09:12.900 --> 09:15.233
Um, we're just practicing
for a game show, Lanny.

09:16.200 --> 09:18.266
Yeah, if you're looking for Matt,
we haven't seen him all day.

09:19.233 --> 09:20.600
[MATT GIGGLING]

09:21.300 --> 09:22.500
MATT: Doh!

09:23.633 --> 09:24.900
[MATT SNEEZES]

09:28.867 --> 09:32.834
MATT: [IN NASAL VOICE] Hey, I'll bet
Matt's upstairs hiding under the bed.

09:34.266 --> 09:36.567
Ow! Ugh...

09:36.633 --> 09:38.867
Okay, don't give me that look, Lanny.

09:38.934 --> 09:42.667
You've only won this round.
The game continues.

09:42.734 --> 09:44.500
One, two, three...

09:46.800 --> 09:47.967
[DOOR SHUTS]

09:48.633 --> 09:52.333
So, anyway, I think we need to
spend more time working on the stunts

09:52.400 --> 09:53.667
than trying to learn Spanish.

09:53.734 --> 09:55.800
Because Carlos is going to
translate for us.

09:55.867 --> 09:57.233
We have to be good at the game.

09:57.800 --> 09:59.700
All right, if you think so.

09:59.967 --> 10:02.333
I guess. What do you think?

10:03.667 --> 10:04.667
<i>Bueno.</i>

10:05.900 --> 10:07.867
What in the world does <i>"bueno"</i> mean?

10:08.934 --> 10:09.934
[GORDO SIGHS]

10:11.133 --> 10:12.333
[GIGGLES]

10:14.433 --> 10:15.934
[CHEERING]

10:17.166 --> 10:19.900
[ANNOUNCER SPEAKING SPANISH]

10:26.100 --> 10:28.367
[AUDIENCE CHEERING AND CLAPPING]

10:30.533 --> 10:33.400
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

10:42.734 --> 10:45.233
<i>Vamonos, vamonos, vamonos para el oro!</i>

10:45.333 --> 10:47.533
-[LOUD CHEERING]
-[SPEAKS SPANISH]

10:47.600 --> 10:49.066
[ULULATING]

10:50.967 --> 10:53.333
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

10:56.400 --> 10:58.734
What Mexican muralist
painted <i>Aztec World?</i>

10:58.800 --> 10:59.967
[WHISPERING]

11:01.233 --> 11:03.900
Ooh. My parents took me
to an exhibit of this guy.

11:03.967 --> 11:05.633
Uh, Diego Rivera.

11:05.700 --> 11:07.633
-[SPEAKING SPANISH]
-GORDO: Yes!

11:07.700 --> 11:10.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

11:10.066 --> 11:12.633
Yes! We'll get some bonus points
before we even start.

11:12.700 --> 11:13.767
Yeah!

11:13.834 --> 11:15.633
Good thing Miranda knows
more about her culture

11:15.700 --> 11:18.300
than I know about being Scottish,
Irish, German, Dutch, Polish,

11:18.367 --> 11:20.000
and whatever else I am.

11:20.633 --> 11:22.400
I have to learn about half the world.

11:22.467 --> 11:24.800
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

11:27.333 --> 11:28.800
[AUDIENCE WHISTLING AND CHEERING]

11:28.867 --> 11:30.667
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYS]

11:30.734 --> 11:32.800
ALEJANDRO: [SPEAKING SPANISH]

11:36.567 --> 11:38.233
We have to pop balloons
in between our chests.

11:38.300 --> 11:40.667
The team that pops the most
in one minute wins. Okay?

11:40.734 --> 11:41.767
LIZZIE: Okay.

11:41.834 --> 11:43.867
<i>Vamonos, vamonos, vamonos para el oro!</i>

11:45.266 --> 11:47.533
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

11:51.767 --> 11:54.233
...ninety-nine, 100.

11:56.467 --> 11:59.667
Ready or not, 'cause here I come.

11:59.734 --> 12:02.133
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

13:23.467 --> 13:25.567
[PLAYFUL MUSIC]

13:31.800 --> 13:33.567
Well played, my friend.

13:33.900 --> 13:35.834
But there's one more round to go,

13:35.900 --> 13:40.200
and I promise you,
you are so not going to find me.

13:42.300 --> 13:44.800
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

13:47.567 --> 13:52.233
Oh, oh, oh. He says,
"Listen, ice cube, dice, television"?

13:52.300 --> 13:54.700
Uh, um... Oh! Las Vegas!

13:54.767 --> 13:57.333
No, no, no, no.
What do they have in common?

13:57.900 --> 13:58.900
They're all square!

13:58.967 --> 14:00.767
-Look in the square baskets!
-Okay.

14:03.734 --> 14:04.767
[LIZZIE EXCLAIMS]

14:06.033 --> 14:07.800
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

14:08.333 --> 14:09.700
Come on, come on, come on, come on!

14:09.767 --> 14:11.867
We got to find the rest
of Gordo's bullfighter suit.

14:11.934 --> 14:13.200
What is he saying?

14:13.266 --> 14:15.433
Uh... Drawers, drawers, drawers.

14:15.767 --> 14:17.934
"Drawers"? What's that
supposed to mean?

14:18.000 --> 14:20.166
-Let's look in the drawers!
-Oh!

14:23.533 --> 14:24.533
[SHRIEKS]

14:32.867 --> 14:35.934
Hey, that really looks pretty good.
This is a good look for you.

14:36.000 --> 14:38.133
Yeah. Can you guys hurry up?
My pants are itchy.

14:38.200 --> 14:40.000
I found the cape! I found the cape!

14:40.300 --> 14:42.066
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

14:42.133 --> 14:44.233
Uh... "Top it off from the bottom."

14:44.300 --> 14:45.967
Oh, something on top of a bull.

14:46.033 --> 14:49.166
A bull has to sit on Gordo's head?
That makes no sense.

14:49.233 --> 14:50.900
Miranda, uh, a hat.

14:51.567 --> 14:53.333
A hat! Yes, that's good!

14:53.400 --> 14:55.333
And it's got to go from the bottom?

14:55.633 --> 14:58.100
Bottom, bottom, the bottom...
The bottom!

14:59.633 --> 15:01.800
-[EXCLAIMS IN SPANISH]
-[YELLS]

15:02.800 --> 15:05.433
I have a feeling <i>cuidado</i>
means either "look out"

15:05.500 --> 15:07.600
or "blondie's about to get squashed."

15:08.667 --> 15:09.834
-[RUMBLING]
-Oh, my gosh!

15:09.934 --> 15:11.500
[ALEJANDRO SPEAKING SPANISH]

15:13.400 --> 15:14.734
[CRASHING]

15:18.834 --> 15:20.400
[JUBILANT MUSIC PLAYING]

15:29.100 --> 15:30.333
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

15:30.400 --> 15:33.000
Yes! We win! We win!

15:33.066 --> 15:36.133
We get to go to the bonus round! Whoo!

15:41.367 --> 15:43.367
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

15:51.734 --> 15:53.133
Uh... Huh?

15:53.767 --> 15:57.567
He says you have to pick roles for us
to play from that board.

15:59.400 --> 16:00.567
Okay, okay.

16:01.100 --> 16:03.166
Gordo, the matador.

16:03.967 --> 16:06.266
Miranda, whatever this is,
you can be it.

16:06.767 --> 16:08.600
I can be the <i>"cabal"</i> thing.

16:09.667 --> 16:11.800
Carlos can be the, um, orange thing.

16:15.000 --> 16:16.333
[LAUGHING]

16:18.133 --> 16:19.734
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

16:22.100 --> 16:23.233
Lizzie!

16:23.300 --> 16:25.500
You made me the Aztec Bird-Snake god.

16:26.033 --> 16:27.500
That means I get separated
from the team.

16:27.567 --> 16:28.533
[MONTEZUMA LAUGHS]

16:28.834 --> 16:30.900
Don't make him go away! We need him!

16:32.033 --> 16:34.033
Okay, I've got about 30 seconds

16:34.100 --> 16:36.266
to brush up on a thousand years
of Mexican culture.

16:36.333 --> 16:38.233
Sorry, guys. Good luck with your game.

16:38.600 --> 16:39.633
[INAUDIBLE]

16:41.300 --> 16:43.567
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

16:45.700 --> 16:46.700
Huh?

16:46.767 --> 16:49.100
I feel like I've just transferred
into a school from Indonesia.

16:49.700 --> 16:51.533
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

17:00.734 --> 17:02.367
What does that mean?
What does that mean?

17:02.433 --> 17:04.800
I must have soaked up
some Spanish in my life.

17:05.567 --> 17:06.567
Nothing.

17:06.633 --> 17:08.233
What are we supposed to do?

17:08.400 --> 17:09.700
How should I know?

17:09.767 --> 17:12.066
Maybe we're
rice pudding delivery people.

17:12.133 --> 17:13.266
We put it in the boxes

17:13.333 --> 17:15.266
and then deliver it
to the other side of the stage.

17:15.333 --> 17:16.567
That seems way too easy.

17:16.967 --> 17:19.867
Maybe we're supposed to
hop over the other boxes as we go.

17:19.934 --> 17:21.166
Hey, it's worth a try.

17:24.000 --> 17:25.133
No, no, no, no, no.

17:25.200 --> 17:27.567
You're supposed to build a pyramid
with the boxes.

17:29.934 --> 17:31.433
Use the pudding for cement.

17:31.900 --> 17:33.333
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

17:40.033 --> 17:41.033
[LIZZIE SHRIEKS]

17:41.100 --> 17:42.266
I am totally lost.

17:42.333 --> 17:45.266
I have no idea what to do
and people are laughing at me.

17:45.600 --> 17:46.767
Quit laughing.

17:46.967 --> 17:49.500
What am I, a clown?
I'm here to amuse you?

17:49.900 --> 17:51.934
Okay, that is not right.

17:52.000 --> 17:54.633
Maybe we're supposed to
eat the rice pudding.

17:54.700 --> 17:56.867
If we were supposed to
eat the rice pudding,

17:56.934 --> 17:58.967
why would they give us
all these other boxes?

17:59.033 --> 18:00.033
They wouldn't.

18:00.567 --> 18:02.000
Then why should we eat it?

18:02.066 --> 18:03.400
'Cause I like rice pudding.

18:04.367 --> 18:05.367
[MIRANDA GASPS]

18:06.667 --> 18:08.900
They're laughing.
That's obviously not right.

18:08.967 --> 18:10.467
No, but it's tasty.

18:11.467 --> 18:13.967
Maybe we're supposed to
dunk the pudding into the boxes.

18:14.200 --> 18:16.767
-Yeah, I'm sure that's it.
-It's worth a try.

18:16.834 --> 18:18.600
What are you doing?
You're wasting pudding!

18:19.200 --> 18:21.100
[SCOFFS] I am trying to win.

18:21.166 --> 18:22.900
-Would you give it up?
-[GRUNTS ANGRILY]

18:23.900 --> 18:26.867
-[GASPS, CHUCKLES]
-GORDO: Oh.

18:27.433 --> 18:29.233
Why did you do that?

18:30.133 --> 18:31.367
It was an accident.

18:32.033 --> 18:34.000
Oh. Well, so was this.

18:34.066 --> 18:35.333
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

18:41.767 --> 18:43.233
It's a good thing you like pudding.

18:43.700 --> 18:46.200
Yeah, well, you know what?
You should try some.

18:46.266 --> 18:48.333
-[GASPS]
-[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

18:48.767 --> 18:50.600
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

18:50.667 --> 18:52.800
[CHUCKLING, SQUEALING]

18:59.033 --> 19:00.033
Ha.

19:00.500 --> 19:02.333
-[AUDIENCE WHISTLING]
-Oh!

19:05.433 --> 19:07.467
[SQUEALING, LAUGHING]

19:08.367 --> 19:10.300
<i>El oro es mio! </i>

19:13.433 --> 19:15.100
[MUMBLING]

19:20.500 --> 19:23.133
Finally, while <i>mehndi</i> tattoos
are very popular here,

19:23.200 --> 19:25.934
most of you probably don't know
that they derive from

19:26.000 --> 19:29.200
the centuries-old cultural
and religious tradition in India.

19:31.900 --> 19:35.033
Very good, Mr. Gordon.
Now we'll hear from Miss McGuire.

19:35.333 --> 19:37.800
Well, for my report,
I thought it would be a good idea

19:37.867 --> 19:39.800
to go on a Spanish-language game show.

19:40.734 --> 19:41.967
Do you understand, Li?

19:42.400 --> 19:45.800
Like <i>Hollywood Squares?</i>
"Whoopi Goldberg to block?"

19:45.867 --> 19:49.133
[CHUCKLES] Yeah, like that,
only stickier.

19:49.200 --> 19:50.834
And before I did that,

19:50.900 --> 19:53.100
I didn't realize
how hard it is to be in a place

19:53.166 --> 19:55.633
where you don't understand
the language or customs.

19:56.066 --> 19:59.000
Or what to do with a box
and a bunch of rice pudding.

19:59.767 --> 20:02.467
And now I realize that I should learn
about other people's cultures

20:03.133 --> 20:04.567
because we're all here together,

20:04.633 --> 20:07.333
and it would be much easier
if we all understood each other.

20:07.633 --> 20:10.667
And believe me, now I know
what it's like not to understand.

20:11.533 --> 20:12.700
It's like being laughed at

20:12.767 --> 20:14.867
and covered in rice pudding
is what it's like.

20:15.233 --> 20:17.633
So, I'm sorry
if I lost my patience with you

20:17.700 --> 20:19.633
because you don't get
everything right away.

20:19.700 --> 20:20.967
I won't do that anymore.

20:21.633 --> 20:24.033
-I understand.
-[CHUCKLES]

20:24.100 --> 20:25.400
Wise words, Miss McGuire.

20:25.633 --> 20:27.967
Anyway, um, I picked somewhere else.

20:30.934 --> 20:32.166
[SIGHS]

20:32.233 --> 20:35.400
The culture of Indonesia
is both ancient and modern.

20:35.600 --> 20:38.900
Stretching across hundreds of islands
in Southeast Asia,

20:38.967 --> 20:41.500
among them Bali and Jakarta.

20:41.567 --> 20:44.300
Indonesian culture reflects
both land and sea.

20:45.367 --> 20:47.000
[INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER TV]

20:48.600 --> 20:51.266
Hey, Lanny, if you've given up,

20:51.333 --> 20:53.934
aren't you supposed to yell
"ollie, ollie, oxen free"?

20:58.000 --> 20:59.633
Okay. [CLEARS THROAT]

20:59.700 --> 21:00.967
Stupid question.

21:03.233 --> 21:05.800
Okay, Lanny, uh,
getting a little bored.

21:07.367 --> 21:09.367
Getting a little hungry, too.

21:10.934 --> 21:12.700
Hurry up and find me, Lanny!

21:15.800 --> 21:17.000
Uh-oh.

21:17.600 --> 21:19.533
Lanny? Lanny!

21:20.033 --> 21:21.633
Lanny!

21:21.700 --> 21:23.300
[TRAIN HORN TOOTS]

21:24.834 --> 21:26.000
A-B camera mark!

21:30.567 --> 21:31.567
[LAUGHTER]

21:33.600 --> 21:35.967
Well played, my... [LAUGHING]

21:36.033 --> 21:38.133
Come on, come on,
come on, come on... Ooh!

21:38.400 --> 21:40.233
Dude. We can't win that way, Adam!

21:40.300 --> 21:41.767
[ALL LAUGH]

21:41.834 --> 21:43.000
We can't win anyway.

21:43.066 --> 21:45.400
At least this way, I get to go home
with a stomach full of rice pudding.

21:45.467 --> 21:46.700
-Sorry!
-[BOTH LAUGH]

21:46.767 --> 21:48.567
Let's dance! Let's dance!

21:49.333 --> 21:50.500
Whoa!

21:51.200 --> 21:53.100
[LAUGHTER]

21:53.667 --> 21:54.767
I'm slipping.

21:55.734 --> 21:58.200
WOMAN: That's it. That's a good one.

21:58.834 --> 22:00.467
Okay, this is not fun anymore.

22:02.266 --> 22:04.266
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
